00:03:47.919 --> 00:03:55.119
for what we call the Office of Performance and Innovation. Spent about a year and a half

00:03:55.119 --> 00:04:03.759
in that role. And up until then, our Chief Data Officer position had been in our IT agency,

00:04:03.759 --> 00:04:11.839
so Baltimore City Information Technology, reporting for our CIO. About two years ago,

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:18.160
when we got a new administration, Mayor Brandon Scott came in. We also added a new position

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:22.559
called the City Administrator, which is kind of like a Chief Operating Officer for the city.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:29.679
The decision was made to move the Chief Data Officer role out of our IT agency and to report

00:04:29.679 --> 00:04:35.440
to our City Administrator. So it definitely kind of raised the profile of data within the

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:41.279
administration, provided kind of executive leadership support around data and how to use

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:46.799
it more strategically. And so when the role was moved over to the Mayor's office, that's when

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:53.760
I took the role. So yeah, coming up on two years in that role, that's just incredible.

00:04:55.119 --> 00:05:02.880
So over the last two years, part of the rationale for moving it into the Mayor's office was to put

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:11.279
a little bit more emphasis, obviously on strategy and how to use data and analytics quite a bit more

00:05:11.279 --> 00:05:20.799
strategically than we had been, but also data governance. So we recognized data quality

00:05:20.799 --> 00:05:26.399
continues to be an issue. There are constantly questions, and this is true of any city government

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:34.000
or any jurisdiction really, around when you can and can't share data. What are the best uses?

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:41.679
What uses should we not pursue of data? So data governance is also kind of one of those large

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:51.519
