two and a half and he's just leaning really hard into that terrible two mode,

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:36.959
just really growing into it. So it's pandemic has been fun for raising kids. A lot of fun.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:46.559
So that's mostly my free time. I read a lot and I'm into road cycling quite a bit, but

00:07:47.359 --> 00:07:53.040
you know, it's mostly the kids these days. That's great. Happy birthday to them.

00:07:54.799 --> 00:07:58.640
Well, we're waiting for some questions to come in from everybody. It sounds like there's a lot

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:05.519
of change across the organization and a lot of new data roles. And I was curious how you're going

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:11.440
about building data literacy through city government. Yeah, that's a great question.

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:15.679
It has grown by leaps and bounds, even just in the five years since I've been here.

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:21.519
There were a few things that I've been kind of either pursuing,

00:08:25.679 --> 00:08:33.039
and then more generally how it's kind of gone for the city. So similar to this group, Rachel,

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:37.440
like one of the first things I did when I came into city government was kind of stealing from

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:44.880
my old, my previous job was, so I came into the mayor's office as a data scientist, but I didn't

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:51.599
know who were all the data people in all the different agencies. So created a, we called it

00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:57.119
the data center for excellence, which was basically just a once a month, you know, basically hangout.

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:02.960
Someone might present some of the work that they're involved in, or, you know, maybe a new tool

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:09.520
they're trying out, issues they're having. So that was one of the first communities of practice we

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:15.039
kind of established around data and city government, and that was meant to, again, kind of

00:09:15.679 --> 00:09:22.559
connect the data people. There are a couple of things, so that was a few years ago. There have

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:28.320
been a few other, like we have a women in data group now kind of forming a community of practice

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:38.159
and a safe space for women and minorities in the data. Most recently, though, it's been more of a

00:09:38.159 --> 00:09:43.919
concerted effort, especially as I've taken on the role of chief data officer. There are a couple of

00:09:43.919 --> 00:09:51.760
places. One is launching a data academy. So we have been piloting it maybe for the last two months

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:56.799
with the Center for Government Excellence. This is another Bloomberg funded group, but they're

00:09:56.799 --> 00:10:04.960
at Johns Hopkins, literally right around the corner from me. And yeah, so we've been developing

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:13.280
a curriculum for the data academy. Where we've chosen to focus is, it'd be very easy to start

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:17.919
creating some kind of curriculum that's for data analysts and data scientists, right? Like,

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:24.799
here are the tools we use in city government, you know, here's like intermediate to advanced power BI

00:10:24.799 --> 00:10:31.760
or, you know, whatever the case might be. But instead, where we chose to focus was on folks

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:38.799
with little or no data literacy. So think about like your frontline workers, your solid waste

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:46.000
collection crews, your housing inspector, like those folks. And so we've named a few different

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.679
tracks within the academy that we're working on. But the first one that we've really given a lot

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:57.280
of focus is this kind of foundations of data literacy, which is really just about, you know,

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:00.640
what are data? How does it show up in your life? How does it show up in your work?

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:08.320
So trying to start at kind of, you know, the very foundational level so we can make sure we're

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:17.200
bringing everyone along and growing data literacy. Another area that's, and so we're actually right

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:22.479
in the middle of trying to consolidate a lot of these disparate efforts around data literacy

00:11:22.479 --> 00:11:28.719
into a more comprehensive workforce strategy. Another component is around our job classifications.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:35.440
So in government, there's always, you know, your job, your functional job title might be data

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:41.679
scientist. But for us, we still have actual classifications that are more like operations

00:11:41.679 --> 00:11:50.479
manager or operations officer. We are working with our IT department to modernize a lot of

00:11:50.479 --> 00:11:57.440
tech and data related classifications so that we can then work with our agencies so that they know

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:04.400
better what they're actually looking for. I know it's similar in the industry where if the

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:10.159
organization is relatively new to data scientists, they think they need a data scientist first.

00:12:10.719 --> 00:12:15.520
And so they hire a data scientist, but that person might quickly get burned out because what they

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:21.679
really end up doing is entirely data cleaning or creating a better data collection tool in the

00:12:21.679 --> 00:12:28.320
first place, which was kind of my, if I'm honest, that was what my role was like when I initially

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:36.479
came in. So getting agencies to see that there's a whole, like, universe of data roles and trying to

00:12:36.479 --> 00:12:43.599
fit the best, you know, the best one to their needs. So that's another area where there's a lot

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:49.599
about a lot of talk and a lot of work going into growing kind of data literacy within government.

