00:22:22.079 --> 00:22:29.839
snowplow optimization example, NC Libby. Other cities, other cities, especially places like

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:38.160
Rochester, you know, a lot of Northern cities have, have wrestled with that for sure.

00:22:39.119 --> 00:22:43.280
We're, Baltimore is one of those cities where like we get a dusting of snow and the whole city

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:50.400
shuts down because it happens so infrequently that we don't, we can't build up that amount of

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:55.359
capacity to deal with it for the, like the rare times we get lots of snow, but places like

00:22:55.359 --> 00:22:59.920
Rochester where it's like day in and day out for six months. Yeah. They've, they've definitely

00:22:59.920 --> 00:23:06.400
worked on those routes. I see a few anonymous questions that came through and I want to make

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:12.479
sure I get to those too. And one was what about hardware and cloud infrastructure? Do you have

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:19.760
to deal with legacy systems? Does the new money allow you to upgrade? Yeah, good question. Yes,

00:23:20.319 --> 00:23:27.599
about legacy systems. This year our IT department, so there's, there's, I, I have a little bit,

00:23:27.599 --> 00:23:32.959
so chief data officer roles kind of like run the spectrum in terms of responsibilities and where

00:23:32.959 --> 00:23:38.640
they are, where they're situated organizationally. I have a little bit less control over architecture.

00:23:39.199 --> 00:23:48.000
That said, yes, there are tons of legacy applications and infrastructure to deal with.

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:54.880
This year we're targeting finally decommissioning our mainframe, which right now still runs

00:23:56.479 --> 00:24:01.199
some of our environmental citations and some of our revenue collections and that kind of thing.

00:24:01.839 --> 00:24:08.719
So we're looking to like replace that. There's also a legacy system with our housing department

00:24:08.719 --> 00:24:18.079
that was homegrown by one person that housing department had hired who was there for 20 years,

00:24:18.079 --> 00:24:23.520
wasn't well documented. They of course left and now, you know, we're kind of picking up the scraps

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:30.560
on that system and it does all of our code enforcement and a whole host of other housing,

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:37.439
housing department functions. So yeah, legacy systems continue to be a challenge. Luckily,

00:24:37.439 --> 00:24:43.359
like we have an IT department that's kind of on it right now and, and has plans to, to,

00:24:43.359 --> 00:24:50.160
to mitigate a lot of that. And so as those things get replaced, you know, we only have

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:55.439
up to go in terms of data quality. We just over the last two years have rolled out Workday as our

00:24:55.439 --> 00:25:02.079
new ERP, enterprise resource planning system. That in and of itself, I think has addressed a

00:25:02.079 --> 00:25:09.199
lot of finance and HR data quality issues. So yeah, we're, we're making moves in that direction.

00:25:09.199 --> 00:25:16.800
Yes, there's legacy systems, but I challenge you all to find a chief data officer in another city

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:25.520
who doesn't reckon with that sometimes. And as far as cloud goes, yeah, we, so for one,

00:25:25.520 --> 00:25:32.560
our GIS team is working hard on moving a lot, a lot of our GIS layers and infrastructure over to

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:39.760
cloud. Of course it's with Esri, as is our open Baltimore, our open data platform.

00:25:41.359 --> 00:25:46.160
We're, I think it's, it's picking your battles and where you're going to get the most bang for

00:25:46.160 --> 00:25:54.880
the buck at the moment for us. I'm looking to pilot a couple of tools to move to cloud. So

00:25:56.160 --> 00:26:01.680
one that I'll mention is we over the summer partnered with a group at Carnegie Mellon

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:08.239
called the Data Science for Social Good. You may know this already, but Baltimore has like

00:26:08.239 --> 00:26:14.479
a lot of vacant buildings. And when a building sits vacant for long enough, rooftops tend to

00:26:14.479 --> 00:26:20.560
become an issue. And back in January of last year, we had three firefighters killed when a rooftop

00:26:21.439 --> 00:26:26.160
was in a, it was a fully involved fire, rooftop collapsed on the three firefighters and were

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:33.760
killed. So we're using, we partnered with Carnegie Mellon to develop an AI tool that

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:42.479
will detect collapsed roofs based on our aerial flyover imagery. We'll, every year we get new

00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:50.319
flyover imagery, which means every year we'll want to refine and update the model

00:26:51.199 --> 00:26:55.520
and get new predictions so we can find any new buildings that might have rooftop issues.

00:26:58.239 --> 00:27:04.000
But we need better, like we're not, I can't, we can't run that on someone's local machine.

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:09.760
So that's a good opportunity to start pushing the bounds of what we can do in cloud.

00:27:10.319 --> 00:27:17.359
So that's, that's one, yeah, we're looking for a couple of places to definitely move that way.

