because it's ARPA funding. And so, and not only that, but like, you know, all aware of kind of,

00:29:14.479 --> 00:29:21.199
one, hiring challenges right now in the market, but two, just hiring process in terms of city

00:29:21.199 --> 00:29:30.000
functions. And so they rightly recognize that actually getting that team stood up, hiring

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:36.560
people is a win. It may not like have built you, you know, a new service for a resident or fixed

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:43.520
anything yet, but that is a win. And I think we're lucky enough that our mayor like recognizes that.

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:48.880
So we have kind of executive leadership that recognizes, that is willing to like kind of

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:57.680
celebrate some of the smaller, more inward focused wins. And then, yeah, like there's a

00:29:57.680 --> 00:30:04.000
pretty, and honestly, for some of them, there is a pretty direct, even though it sounds ostensibly

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:11.040
about, you know, internal capacity or being inward focused, there's a pretty direct line and theory

00:30:11.040 --> 00:30:17.119
of change from if we improve data literacy by building this data academy program, we will

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:24.479
improve service delivery to our residents. Or if we create this digital services team and even

00:30:24.479 --> 00:30:30.640
getting, you know, a handful of new experts in civic technology, and we will build better services

00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:38.800
for residents. So now that's, I'm lucky enough, again, being in kind of the public sector space

00:30:39.119 --> 00:30:47.760
where, you know, it's, if you can't draw that line, chances are you aren't doing that thing in

00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:53.359
the first place, or you're not setting that goal in the first place, you know. So I don't know if

00:30:53.359 --> 00:30:59.439
that helps or answers the question, but a couple of initial thoughts on it, I guess.

00:30:59.439 --> 00:31:09.920
Awesome. Raha, I see you had asked a question in the chat as well. Would you want to jump in next?

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:15.839
Sure, good timing. I just ran down to make sure my Amazon package wasn't stolen.

00:31:15.839 --> 00:31:17.680
Oh, I'm glad that it wasn't.

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:24.319
No, I got there in time. No, so I live in Baltimore too, and there's definitely a lot

00:31:24.319 --> 00:31:30.239
of issues here that I'm concerned about that I feel data could really address. But part of that

00:31:30.239 --> 00:31:36.400
is making sure that you're able to collect the right data, that you're able to do analysis on

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:42.160
it, and that someone listens to that and makes a decision. So I wanted to see if you had any

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:48.239
examples of where that has been done or where you see it heading. Like, will 311 be better?

00:31:48.239 --> 00:31:52.719
Will street sweeping be better? Can you make sure certain neighborhoods aren't underserved?

00:31:53.439 --> 00:31:55.040
Yep, yep, it's a great question.

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:06.479
Maybe a couple of different scales I can offer. So one about, well, this would have been just

00:32:06.479 --> 00:32:14.479
before the pandemic, so I cannot believe it's been three years. So we identified a pretty big

00:32:14.479 --> 00:32:21.119
backlog in DPW in terms of cleaning service requests in the city. This was upwards of,

00:32:21.119 --> 00:32:29.280
I want to say there were 15 or 17,000 service requests. That was a backlog. So these are things

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:35.359
that had accumulated. It was right in the middle of the summer. So a couple of things happened.

00:32:38.560 --> 00:32:46.640
One was we worked with DPW basically to even identify that as an issue and start discussing

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:55.040
how we were going to deal with it. And part of that was actually, we collected a few parameters

00:32:55.040 --> 00:33:00.640
from them. And this is more of like an engineering approach as opposed to a data science approach,

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:05.839
but we built a small kind of heuristic model where you could modify kind of the number of

00:33:05.839 --> 00:33:14.800
crews that were online and some of the distribution of where the SRs were and that kind of thing

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:20.719
to try and estimate how quickly we could drive things down. And so you can manipulate how many

00:33:20.719 --> 00:33:27.599
crews you have where in the city and you could see whether we might or might not get to clearing

00:33:27.599 --> 00:33:33.760
out the backlog and when. Because I think we had set a particular goal of getting that eliminated

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:45.920
by a certain date. Yeah, I can't remember the exact timing. So one was, and that was a bit of a

00:33:48.400 --> 00:33:53.439
process of convincing that, yeah, you can ask for their parameters and plug it into your little

00:33:53.439 --> 00:33:57.119
model, but all they have to do is say, I don't know how this model works or I don't believe

00:33:57.119 --> 00:34:01.920
your model to like not want to drive their decisions. They're not going to listen to it. So

00:34:02.800 --> 00:34:07.199
it was a very simplistic model that they could, you know, you took them along each step and say,

00:34:07.199 --> 00:34:13.360
okay, if you've got this many crews here, that means you could complete how many SRs, you know,

00:34:13.360 --> 00:34:23.120
that day. The other half of that one was they used to divide the city up into quadrants and they had

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:29.520
hard restrictions on how many crews they would put in each quadrant, which meant if a quadrant,

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:35.600
if a crew called off in a quadrant, it impacted that quadrant, but no one else. But the issue was

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:40.080
if all the SRs, if all the demand was in another part of the city or in that part of the city,

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:45.760
you couldn't pull a crew from elsewhere that had a low workload into that area. So it was,

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:51.840
they were placing arbitrary constraints on their deployments. We got them basically to eliminate

00:34:51.840 --> 00:34:59.040
that way of working, that kind of strategy, because we proved out that you're exacerbating

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:07.679
the issue by, you know, arbitrarily placing these constraints on your crews. So that was a really

00:35:07.679 --> 00:35:13.520
good win. And by the way, I think there was a Sun article at the time about it. The southeast

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:18.959
quadrant of the city was getting far better service than the rest of the city. So there was

00:35:18.959 --> 00:35:24.560
a massive equity issue. So again, just by some simple analysis and showing them and bringing

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:28.959
them along, we were able to make, you know, convince them to make some better decisions.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:37.840
The most recent example of getting folks to make decisions was, so DPW is one of those where it's

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:42.879
a little bit tougher to, they're a little bit further behind, I would say, on their growth

00:35:42.879 --> 00:35:47.280
curves in terms of data literacy and using data to make decisions. At the other end-

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:48.879
They're losing their leadership.

00:35:48.879 --> 00:35:49.679
What's that?

00:35:49.679 --> 00:35:53.040
They're also losing their leadership. The head of DPW resigned.

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:55.520
Yeah, just a couple of days ago. Yeah, it was like two days ago, right?

00:35:58.239 --> 00:36:03.600
But did they even collect the right data in the first place? Is it available? Because I know

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:09.120
what you were talking about the cleanup crews, I think we have 16 total, which is nowhere near

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:15.280
enough. And so there's something that they need. I don't, I mean, it's, you don't make hiring

00:36:15.280 --> 00:36:21.040
decisions, obviously. There's some gap of how they recruit and where they get people to do what,

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:26.959
I mean, DPW especially with solid waste. But across the board, are people collecting the

00:36:26.959 --> 00:36:31.840
right type of data that allows you to do the analysis to make decisions? Or do you then

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:34.879
request them to make, to collect that data? How do you do that?

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:44.000
In a lot of the, I mean, there's kind of the diminishing returns, right? Like, so 311 definitely

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:50.159
covers a lot of our city services and certainly for something like public works, you know,

00:36:50.159 --> 00:36:58.800
311 is meant to be the record of, you know, the source of truth. And so, yeah, we direct

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:04.320
residents to 311. That's what we look at internally to determine service levels.

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:12.719
And now that said, we continue to have kind of quality issues around 311, like you raised that,

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:17.439
you know, for example, there's still the concern that something gets closed, but the work wasn't

00:37:17.439 --> 00:37:24.000
performed. That issue, like, it's completely dependent on what SR type you're looking at,

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.639
because there's 200 service request types and each of them is an entirely different

00:37:29.199 --> 00:37:37.360
workflow. It's a different crew. It's different people involved. So anyways, all that to say,

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:43.840
like, I would say on the whole, we're collecting the right data for some of the bigger areas.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:50.959
I think there are some smaller areas where we definitely need better data. One that comes to

00:37:50.959 --> 00:38:01.520
mind is, it's related to illegal dumping, but our transfer stations, you know, where a small hauler

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:07.120
truck could go and drop off their loads, you know, maybe they're cleaning up debris from, you know,

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:12.080
a construction site or something. So all they do is, you know, they've got a pickup truck and they

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:19.280
run a truckload of debris. We have really long line waits at those drop-off stations.

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:25.840
And we've always had the, we've always hypothesized that because there are those long

00:38:25.840 --> 00:38:31.040
waits and these guys are just trying to make money, that if they see a long wait, they're

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:35.840
going to leave and go dump their load somewhere they shouldn't be dumping it. And so that

00:38:35.840 --> 00:38:41.840
exacerbates illegal dumping issues. The problem is we don't have either a digital

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:48.959
licensing or check-in process for the transfer stations. So we can't actually monitor, you know,

00:38:48.959 --> 00:38:55.439
if you have a small hauler license, how often are you actually checking in at the transfer station?

00:38:55.439 --> 00:38:59.760
Because if we see that you have an active small hauler license, but you're never checking in

00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:05.040
to a transfer station, that might be a signal that they're taking their loads elsewhere.

00:39:06.080 --> 00:39:10.719
But because we don't have any kind of digital tools for doing that check-in process, we aren't

00:39:10.719 --> 00:39:16.560
able to look at that issue all that closely. So there are definitely pockets where we absolutely

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:25.679
need better data. And again, it's always a matter of cities or resource straps, you know, picking,

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.959
and like you said, there's a spectrum of kind of leadership in terms of being data driven. So

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:45.760
it's finding the areas where you've got all the right constraints satisfied to do some good.

