questions here, so I want to jump over to a few others. But Eric, I see you had asked a question

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:12.159
in the chat a bit ago. Do you want to jump in? Sure. It's been fascinating to hear your stories,

00:40:12.159 --> 00:40:16.800
Justin, and really exciting to hear these perspectives. So I'm just kind of curious

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:22.159
as somebody who really appreciates, you know, the tool stack and how we're taking modern approaches

00:40:22.159 --> 00:40:28.239
to data science, what kind of modern tooling are you trying to implement across your workflows,

00:40:28.239 --> 00:40:32.959
especially in the, you know, the government sector where, of course, my collaboration mostly

00:40:32.959 --> 00:40:37.919
with colleagues at the FDA, and I know they tend to have some strict requirements on what they're

00:40:37.919 --> 00:40:43.280
allowed to use and whatnot. So just kind of curious how you're handling those approaches for like

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:51.760
best practice of co-development or releases within your team. Yeah, it's a joint effort with

00:40:51.760 --> 00:41:02.239
our IT department because, you know, for the ransomware attack we had, so we had a ransomware

00:41:02.239 --> 00:41:06.560
attack here three years ago, and a lot of cities have experienced these over the last couple of

00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:12.639
years. It really ground city government completely to a halt. I couldn't access my email for more

00:41:12.639 --> 00:41:20.719
than a month. Coming out of that, there's been a pretty strong emphasis not only on cybersecurity,

00:41:20.719 --> 00:41:26.560
but even just modernizing and professionalizing our IT approach, and so our IT department has

00:41:27.199 --> 00:41:37.439
grown by leaps and bounds in that regard. It's a joint effort because there's, this is one of

00:41:37.439 --> 00:41:42.719
those spaces where there's a little bit of overlap between IT and the technology side, but also data

00:41:42.719 --> 00:41:52.800
analytics and that side of things, and the data governance around it. So things like, we're just

00:41:52.800 --> 00:42:01.520
now getting into like what exactly is our code repo policy. Internally, we have Azure, like the

00:42:01.520 --> 00:42:11.199
IT department's using Azure DevOps now for code and deploying, and so getting our data analysts

00:42:11.199 --> 00:42:18.239
onto that and getting them to recognize the value and bringing that into Azure is important because,

00:42:18.239 --> 00:42:22.000
of course, on the data side and a lot of the civic technology side, you also want to

00:42:22.560 --> 00:42:31.280
build open source tools, and like that's always my preference as well, but a lot of folks who either

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:36.719
come into data science from other areas, they aren't always up to speed on kind of software

00:42:36.719 --> 00:42:42.320
development best practices, and so you do get folks, you know, writing code, maybe code that

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:47.840
doesn't need to be or doesn't belong on GitHub and really doesn't actually need to stay internally.

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:54.399
So that's something we're actually kind of confronting right now is let's get together a

00:42:54.399 --> 00:43:00.000
policy where we all agree this is a great use case for open source. This is where you should make

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:05.360
something open source, and here are the places where we can't make it open source and need to

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:10.800
keep things internal. So there are definitely governance issues there. That's kind of a live

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:17.439
question for us. Yeah, did that answer your question? I can't recall.

00:43:18.719 --> 00:43:23.919
No, that's quite interesting to me, and I can sympathize. In fact, I was on a meeting just before

00:43:23.919 --> 00:43:29.439
this where my colleagues had never heard about GitHub in this upper part of the org, and yeah,

00:43:29.439 --> 00:43:34.080
there's lots of education that we even have to do in our own organizations about some of these

00:43:34.080 --> 00:43:38.560
tooling, but yeah, certainly sounds like you're thinking a lot of the great ideas, and I agree.

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:43.520
There definitely is a lot of overlap that can occur between what you're proposing from a

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:48.239
development, you know, tooling perspective and what IT is trying to serve up, so having that

00:43:48.239 --> 00:43:54.000
relationship solid up front is always really beneficial. The other, and the other

00:43:55.199 --> 00:44:00.080
really big aspect of it for city government or any government really is that

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:06.560
we're an organization of organizations. So in some respects, yes, we have central IT

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:14.239
who can support all of the other agencies. Up until the last couple of years, a lot of agencies

00:44:14.239 --> 00:44:19.439
pursued their own IT, you know, whether they weren't getting good support from central IT or

00:44:19.439 --> 00:44:24.159
weren't moving quickly enough or want to try their own things or wanted to use something different

00:44:24.159 --> 00:44:29.760
than everyone else was using. So there's been a lot of, like, so there's been a federated approach

00:44:30.479 --> 00:44:37.919
very distributed, and so, and that applied to the data folks as well. So

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:43.520
there's an argument to be made that there are things we need to centralize, and

00:44:44.159 --> 00:44:49.040
what were constraints around? The concern is always, well, we don't want to slow down an agency.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:54.800
